{"id":37565,"date":"2019-10-17T13:00:19","date_gmt":"2019-10-17T17:00:19","guid":{"rendered":"https:\/\/jamesclear.vercel.app\/3-2-1\/3-2-1-on-change-margin-of-safety-and-handling-criticism"},"modified":"2022-10-18T15:11:48","modified_gmt":"2022-10-18T19:11:48","slug":"october-17-2019","status":"publish","type":"3-2-1","link":"https:\/\/jamesclear.vercel.app\/3-2-1\/october-17-2019","title":{"rendered":"3-2-1: On change, margin of safety, and handling criticism\u00a0"},"content":{"rendered":"\n<h2 id=\"h-3-ideas-from-me\">3 IDEAS FROM ME<\/h2>\n\n\n\n<p>I.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>&#8220;The idea that &#8216;change is hard&#8217; is one of the biggest myths about human behavior.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>The truth is, you change effortlessly and all the time. The primary job of the brain is to adjust your behavior based on the environment.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>Design a better environment. Change will happen naturally.&#8221;<\/p>\n\n\n\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-css-opacity\"\/>\n\n\n\n<p>II.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>&#8220;A simple way to ensure you are focused on what matters:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>Imagine everything gets wiped. You inherit no tasks or responsibilities from your past or present. Then, add back only what you miss.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>Choose what to add to a blank slate, not what to keep from a full plate.&#8221;<\/p>\n\n\n<div id=\"block_5fac5fc6658c6\" class=\"twitter-share \" data-easygut-id=\"twitter\">\n\t<div><a href=\"https:\/\/ctt.ac\/82f94\"><svg width=\"24\" height=\"27\" viewBox=\"0 0 24 27\" fill=\"none\" xmlns=\"http:\/\/www.w3.org\/2000\/svg\">\n<circle cx=\"12\" cy=\"14\" r=\"12\" fill=\"#EDEADE\"\/>\n<path d=\"M16.3613 12.1406C16.791 11.8184 17.1777 11.4316 17.4785 10.9805C17.0918 11.1523 16.6406 11.2812 16.1895 11.3242C16.6621 11.0449 17.0059 10.6152 17.1777 10.0781C16.748 10.3359 16.2539 10.5293 15.7598 10.6367C15.3301 10.1855 14.75 9.92773 14.1055 9.92773C12.8594 9.92773 11.8496 10.9375 11.8496 12.1836C11.8496 12.3555 11.8711 12.5273 11.9141 12.6992C10.0449 12.5918 8.36